Citations
Date: 7/10/1933
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: <i>Crutch.</i> (1) to cut away the wool round a sheep's tail and hind legs so that he will not foul himself. (2) When sheep are dipped they are shoved under with a thing like an inverted <i>crutch</i>. This is called <i>crutching</i>. (3) The implement used for (2). (C.)
Notes: (Acland Gloss.)

Date: 0/0/1940
Source: Te Waimate
Author: STUDHOLME
Vol / Page: 117
Edition: 1954
Quote: One day whilst trying to `crutch' (push under) some slippery-backed old ewe, my brother Geoffrey fell in amongst the sheep ... and in spite of jumping into the creek ... lost a good deal of skin from dip burns.
